explanation:
- UtAssert_Compare_t (full type/enum definition): You must know the complete definition of the enum/typedef to determine the full set of possible values for CompareType. Dead-code analysis requires checking whether the switch in UtAssert_GetOpText covers every enumerator (or whether some enumerators exist but are never used).
- UtAssert_Compare_* enumerators (EQ, NEQ, LT, GT, LTEQ, GTEQ, BITMASK_SET, BITMASK_UNSET): Although these enumerators appear as case labels, you need the canonical declarations/values to confirm they are the actual enum members and to detect any additional enum constants not covered by the switch. Also needed to ensure there are no duplicate/aliased values that could make some case labels redundant.
- UtAssert_GenericIntegerCompare (definition): This is the only caller in the static call graph. Inspecting its implementation shows how/where CompareType values are produced and which enumerators can actually be passed to UtAssert_GetOpText at runtime. That determines whether any case labels in UtAssert_GetOpText are ever reached (live) or are effectively dead because the caller never produces those values.

(With these symbols you can determine whether the switch covers all possible runtime values passed from callers or whether some branches are never exercised and thus constitute dead code under the MISRA rule.)
